Mixture Model Intuition¶

  • Knowing that there is a difference between the spending of male and female purchases on a platform and given the sales data where males and females are not labeled, we can use k-means to find the clusters in the data.

  • We can also model the spending as Gaussians and try to find the means a standard deviations of each disribution.

    • Each data point is simply a random variate from a gaussian
    • A data point can have a probability density value under each distribution

Finite Mixture Model¶

  • The distribution exhibits two different peaks

    • Those are clearer in the histogram that in the KDE.
    • They would be much more evident if the means of the two distributions were much farther away

  • The total sales distribution is a mixture of precisely two distributions

Finite Mixtures - Cont'd¶

  • Here, the total sales is a finite mixture of two distributions

    • A mixture distribution is the probability distribution of a random variable that is derived from a collection of other random variables

  • Mixtures occur naturally

    • When you study spending on the apple store, the distribution of prices for professional applications may be substantially different from other apps.
      • Ex. prices for apps for doctors, stock traders, frequent travelers, etc. may be substantially different than apps for general public
    • Measuring some phenotype in the population, ex. Height or weight, or blood sugar will undoubtedly contain multiple distributions.
    • etc.

  • Some probabilistic models can account for an infinite number of components (clusters)

    • Used, for instance, in clustering species or documents.

Impracticality of the K-means¶

  • Works well on blobs of data

    • The boundary of each cluster is always circular, with the center of the cluster being the mean

  • Does not work well overlapping clusters; including overlapping blobs

    • No confidence in the uncertainty in the assignment of each point.

  • Here, we need an approach that let us include that uncertainty in the clustering

Modeling a Mixture Distribution¶

  • In the above, we assumed that we know the exact number of males and females

    • The number of males and females should also be a parameter to our model
      • Should sample gender from a binomial (ex. for 500 individuals and a proportion of males/females = 0.7)
        np.random(1, 0.7, 500)

  • A more accurate generative model of the mixture distribution can be derived as follows

Defining the Mixture dsitribution¶

np.random.seed(42)
male_female_prop = 0.45

mean_males = 204
std_males = 31

mean_females = 257
std_females = 28

sales_males =  []
sales_females = []

cluster = []


for i in range(1000):
    gender = np.random.choice([0,1], p = [male_female_prop, 1- male_female_prop])
    if gender == 0:
        cluster.append(0) 
        male_sale = np.random.normal(mean_males, std_males) 
        sales_males.append(male_sale)
    else:
        cluster.append(1)
        female_sale = np.random.normal(mean_females, std_females) 
        sales_females.append(female_sale)
        
        

sales_total = np.concatenate([sales_males, sales_females])

Decomposing the Mixture¶

  • How do we construct a mixture distribution from other random variables?

  • The mixture distribution is simply the sum of the two distribution

    • Each point $x$ is evaluated using $f_male(x)$ and $f_males$ where
      • $ X_{male} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{male},\sigma_{male})$ and $X_{female} \sim \mathcal{N} (\mu_{female},\sigma_{female})$.

  • Recall that:

$$ pdf(x,\mu,\sigma) = \frac{1}{\sigma + \sqrt{2 \pi}} \frac{-1}{2}e^{\left(\frac{{ x - \mu}}{\sigma}\right)^2} $$
  • $\mu$ and $\sigma$ depend on the size of the sample
    • combining $X_{male}$ and $X_{female}$ requires us to normalize by the sample size

Question¶

  • We have access to the two means ($\mu_1$ and $\mu_2$) and two std deviations ($\sigma_1$ and $\sigma_2$) describing two populations $P_1$ and $P_2$

  • Given a new point, $x_1$, how can guess which population the point is most likely to have come from?

Inferring Model Parameters of Gaussian Mixture Model¶

  • The paramter we need to infer here are:
    1. The mean and standard deviation for the males' sales
    2. The mean and standard deviation for the females' sales
    3. The proportion of males to females
  • Catch 22
    • We can easily infer these parameters if we know which point comes from which group
      • compute the mean and std dev. for each group independently
    • if we know the means and std deviations, we could easily assign an unknown point to its distribution
      • compute the probability of each point under each distribution

Key Idea 1¶

  • if we know the which cluster each of the points belong to, then generating the model params is easy

Key Idea 1 - Cont'd¶

  • Computing the mean and standard deviation of each point

Inferring the Likelhood of Each Point Under Each Cluster¶

  • The Likelihood that a data point $x$ came from the blue curve is
$$ p(x| \mu_b, \sigma_b) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_b^2}}exp(-\frac{(x-\mu_b)^2}{2\sigma_b^2}) $$
  • The probability that the point came from the orange curve is
$$ p(x| \mu_o, \sigma_o) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_o^2}}exp(-\frac{(x-\mu_o)^2}{2\sigma_o^2}) $$

Key Idea 2¶

  • Each observation is assumed to belong to a cluster $c_i$ according to membership probabilities that sum up to 1

    • We do not use a “hard” label that assigns a point exclusively to either clusters
  • Observation above has $X\%$ of belonging to the blue cluster and Y% belonging to the orange cluster
    • we compute these probabilities as: $$ X = \frac{{p(x \in \mbox{cl}_b~\mbox{|}~~ \mu_b, \sigma_b)}}{{\sum_{j}{p(x \in \mbox{cl}_b~\mbox{|}~~ \mu_b, \sigma_b) + p(x \in \mbox{cl}_o~\mbox{|}~~ \mu_o, \sigma_o)}}} $$
$$ Y = \frac{{p(x \in \mbox{cl}_o~\mbox{|}~~ \mu_o, \sigma_o)}}{{\sum_{j}{p(x \in \mbox{cl}_b~\mbox{|}~~ \mu_b, \sigma_b) + p(x \in \mbox{cl}_o~\mbox{|}~~ \mu_o, \sigma_o)}}} $$

Using Expectation-Maximization¶

  • Expectation-Maximization (EM) is a popular algorithm used to infer the hidden groupings in situations with interdependence

    • An iterative procedure that alternates between:

  • Pretending that we know the params of each cluster (ex. $mu_i$ and $\sigma_i$)

  • Pretending we know the probability with which each observation belongs to a component

  • We iterate until we see no substantial improvement in our optimizations

Using Expectation-Maximization - Cont'd¶

  • Pretending that we know the params of each cluster

    • We use that information to estimate the probability that each point belongs to each component
    • We do not assign a point to a cluster as in K-Means

  • Pretending we know the probability with which each observation belongs to a component

    • Use that information to estimate the distribution parameters of each cluster
    • Recall that a point does not belowng exclusively to one single cluster
      • This something we need to take into account.

The E-M Algorithm in K-Means¶

  • Although we did not expressively define it as so, K-Means also uses expectation–maximization

    • Choose starting guesses for the location

  • For each point, repeat until converged:

    • E-step: for each point, find its closest mean and assign it to it
    • M-step: for each cluster, update clusters' means, based on all data points in each cluster

E-M Example: The Data¶

  • We are analyzing data in one dimension ($x$)

    • We know the data comes from two clusters but is unlabeled
    • We want to discover the params of those Gaussians

E-M Example: The initialization¶

  • We initialize the distributions parameters using random values for the means and the standard deviations
    • Means can be assigned randomly or using more informed methods, such using a full round of K-Means

E-M Algorithm: Expectation Step¶

  • How likely is each of the points to be from each of the distribution?

    • Given each point, what its pdf given each of the Gaussians?

    • Each point has a little bit of the first distribution and a bit of the second

      • Here we use colors (blue and orange) to illustrate that

E-M Algorithm: Expectation Step¶

  • A point $i$ is $O_i$ orange and $B_i$ blue, where
$$ B_i = \frac{p(x_i| \mu_b, \sigma_b)}{p(x_i| \mu_b, \sigma_b) + p(x_i| \mu_o, \sigma_o)}, $$

and

$$ O_i = \frac{p(x_i| \mu_o, \sigma_o)}{p(x_i| \mu_b, \sigma_b) + p(x_i| \mu_o, \sigma_o)}, $$

  • Recompute the means and the std. deviations of each distribution based on its points

    • Each of the points is going to contribute only its probabilitues worth to computing the params ($B_i$ and $O_i$)

E-M Algorithm: Maximization Step - Cont'd¶

  • Ex. Rather use compute the mean as $\mu_b = \sum x_i/n_b$, we are going to use a weighted average
$$ \mu_b = \frac{\sum {B_i}x_i}{\sum B_i} $$$$ \sigma_b = \frac{\sum {B_i}(x_i - \mu_b)^2}{\sum B_i} $$

  • We compute the variance in a similar fashion by discounting the contributions of each point by its contribution to other clusters

  • It is easier to understand this if you think of it in terms of k-means (the $b_i$s are simply 0 or 1).

    • i.e., in k-means gives all its mass to one point
    • Here, each point gives some value in [0,1] to each of the Gaussians

E-M Algorithm: Maximization Step¶

E-M Algorithm: Second Iteration¶

E-M Algorithm: Final Results¶

  • After multiple iteration, we arrive at a stable solution

Assumptions about EM¶

  • Note that here, we assumed that priors for each cluster are identical, i.e. $P(O) =P(B)$

  • If that's not the case, then we would need to evaluate the priors for each iteration

  • $P(B) = \sum(B_i) / n$

    • it's common to start with equal priors to avoid the possibility that a cluster is squashed
    • if P(O)=0, then our solution never works

  • Similar to k-means, there are no guarantees that EM converges

    • Common to repeat using different initializations

Gaussian Mixture Model¶

  • A data modeling technique which attempts to find a mixture of Gaussian probability distributions that best model the input

  • Assumes the source is Gaussian

    • The Gaussian can be multi-dimensional

  • Instead of assigning a point to a cluster assigns the point to the all clusters $c_i$, each with a probability $p_i$

    • Provides confidence measure about the point being in any of the clusters

  • Uses the EM to identify the param of each component

Multivariate Gaussians¶

  • Data is usually in $d$ dimensions

  • e.g., a mortgage company who wants to predict whether an individual qualify for a mortgage may have the following features:

    • Income
    • Gender
    • Age
    • Years of employment with current employer
    • Credit Score
    • Debt to income ration
    • # traffic citations
    • Credit inquiries
    • # of recent delinquincies

  • Based on the features above, the data is in 10 dimensions

  • Hard or impossible to visualize data above 3 dimnsions in a way that conveys an desired message

    • Try to understand the concept in 2 dimensions

Multivariate Gaussian¶

  • A multivariate Gaussian distribution, or joint Guassian distribution is a generalization of the one-dimensional (univariate) normal distribution to higher dimensions.

    • Bivariate is the generalization of two joint Gaussian distributions

  • A random random vector is said to be k-variate normally distributed if every linear combination of its k components has a univariate normal distribution.

Multivariate Gaussian - Cont'd¶

  • The multivariate normal distribution of a k-dimensional random vector $ \mathbf {X} =(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{k}) $, where

$ X_i \ \sim \ {\mathcal {N}}({\mu_i},\, \sigma_i)$.

and $ \mathbf {X} \ \sim \ {\mathcal {N}}({\boldsymbol {\mu }},\,{\boldsymbol {\Sigma }})$, where $\Sigma$ is the covariance matrix, i.e.,

$ \Sigma _{i,j} = \operatorname {Cov} [X_{i},X_{j}] $

  • Recall that you can think of the covariance as a "sort of" scale free measure of the dependence between two variables $X_i$ and $X_j$
    • Unlike correaltion, covariance, change in scale affects the covariance, which ranges between $-\infty$ and $+\infty$
$$ cov(X_i, X_j) = corr(X_i, X_j) \times \sigma_{X_i}\sigma_{X_j} $$

The Covariance Matrix¶

  • $ \Sigma _{i,j} = \operatorname {Cov} [X_{i},X_{j}] $
    • $ \Sigma _{i,i} = \operatorname {Cov} [X_{i},X_{j}]$
      • That's simply the $var(X_i)$

Bivariate Gaussian¶

  • We are going to model all the data in one go

  • The params of a a mutivariate gaussian are the vector of means $M \in \mathcal{R}^{d} $ and the covariance matrix $\Sigma \in \mathcal{R}^{d \times d}$

How to Determine the Number of Gaussians to Represent the Data?¶

  • Similar Problem to finding the number of means in k-means

    • Use, for instance, Silhouette Index

  • Also, the probabilistic Nature makes it easier to define an objective function

    • This is just the function we want to optimize
    • We can just compute the value of clusters that maximizes the likelihood
